photo.description: zu Brandes 750 Dupl [Georg Friedrich Brandes (1709-1791) was a German jurist, overseer(?) of the University of Göttingen, and collector of books and art. The bulk of his notable library, some 22000 volumes, was sold in 1790 to Peter Friedrich Ludwig, Duke of Oldenburg (1755-1829) and formed the basis of the Landesbibliothek Oldenburg (founded 1792 and still in existence). Brandes also collected engravings and Michel Huber published a 2-volume catalog of the collection under the title Catalogue raisonné du cabinet d'estampes de feu Monsieur Brandes, secrétaire intime de la Chancellerie royale d'Hannovre (Leipzig: Rost, 1792-1794). These engravings appear to have been sold at auction in 1796. Two separate sales were planned: the first at Easter (18 April), comprising the English, German and Italian items; the second at Michaelmas (3 October), comprising items from France and the Netherlands. Cf. "Verkauf des Brandes'schen Kupferstich-Kabinets" in Neue Bibliothek der schönen Wissenschaften und der freyen Künste 56 (1795): 189-190, as well as the two sale catalogues: Premiere partie ou Écoles angloise, allemande et italienne, avec une grande collection de portraits: dont la vente publique se fera à la foire prochaine de Pâques 1796 ... par M. Weigel (Leipzig, 1795) and Seconde partie ou Écoles des Pays-Bas et Francoise: dont la vente publique se fera à la foire prochaine de S. Michel 1796 ... par M. Weigel (Leipzig, 1796). For more information on Brandes's library, including reproductions of his bookplate, see the online exhibition at the Landesbibliothek Oldenburg here, as well as G. Crusius, Aufklärung und Bibliophilie: Der Hannoveraner Sammler Georg Friedrich Brandes und seine Bibliothek (Heidelberg: Winter, 2008). Crusius also deals briefly with the engravings collection. Established form: Brandes, Georg Friedrich, ǂd 1709-1791.] Penn Libraries call number: GC5 B8385 544w All images from this book GC5 B8650 542c All images from this book GC5 J5966 540a All images from this book GC55 B8385 590o All images from this book GC6 B8385 602w All images from this book GC6 B8385 604g All images from this book GC6 B8385 606w All images from this book GC6 B8385 606w2 GC6 B8385 608a All images from this book GC6 B8385 608b All images from this book GC6 B8385 611w All images from this book GC6 B8385 619v GC6 K7403 607e All images from this book

photo.description: Martinus Boxberger Königs Houensis Constat 1/3 fs 2/13 gs [...] Febru:[?] Anno 1560 Hab ich Zu Naumburgk kauft Vnd [...]elt doch Tilemanni Buchleins datum den 1. octob. anno 60 ["Martinus Boxberger Kunigshofensis" appears in the matriculation list of the University of Wittenberg for 1559. Cf. K.E. Förstemann et al., eds., Album Academiae Vitebergensis (Aalen: Scientia Verlag, 1976), Bd. 1, p.. 363. "Tilemanni" probably refers to Tilemann Stella (1525-1589), the author of one of the works bound in this volume, Kurtzer und klarer Bericht vom Gebrauch und Nutz der newen Landtaffeln (Wittenberg: Johann Krafft, 1560). Stella was a scholar and cartographer in the service of Johann Albrecht I, Herzog von Mecklenburg-Schwerin (1525-1576). Established form: Stella, Tilemann, ‡d 1525-1589 Naumburg on the river Saale was noted for its trade fair (Naumburger Messe) from the 13th century onward, though it began losing ground as a trade center to Leipzig in the 16th century.] Penn Libraries call number: IC R2634 557c Other images from this book

photo.description: Bibliotheque du P[eti]t semin[ai]re de Chalons Seminarium Cathalaunense This is a stamp from the (diocesan) Petit seminaire de Châlons, founded by Louis-Antoine de Noailles, 1651-1729, bishop of Châlons, later archbishop of Paris, then given the cap in 1700, who was frequently accused (usually by Jesuits) of being a Jansenist. His support for theological and doctrinal works condemned as Jansenist, and for individuals accused of Jansenism was never sufficiently countered by his seemingly lukewarm repudiation of the heresy. He is frequently confused with other members of the Noailles family. The Grand seminaire de Chalons, also under the patronage of Louis-Antoine de Noailles, later became a Lazarist school. Châlons-sur-Marne became Châlons-en-Champagne by decree of June 11, 1995 Penn Libraries call number: FC65 C6543 C755 All images from this book
